%N A396456 Smallest prime greater than the n-th prime-complete number.
%C A396456 An integer is designated "prime-complete" if and only if it has at least one prime divisor and its prime divisors form a complete contiguous set from 2 to its greatest prime divisor. Equivalently, n is prime-complete iff its distinct prime factors are exactly {2, 3, ..., prime(k)} for some k >= 1. The sequence A055932 comprises all the prime-complete numbers together with the number 1. The number 2, is the first prime-complete number, so a(1) is the first prime following 2, thus 3.
%C A396456 A double (two prime-complete numbers in one prime gap) occurs only for the shared next-primes 37, 97, 487, and 4621; no further double exists below 10^12, and a heuristic based on the density of prime-complete numbers suggests this list of doubles is complete and that no triple occurs. That is, the counting function for prime-complete numbers, A377028(n) - 1, grows sub-polynomially (empirically exp(O(sqrt(log n)))), so prime-complete numbers thin out faster than any polynomial while prime gaps grow only logarithmically. The expected number of further doubles beyond x is therefore a convergent sum, supporting the conjecture that the complete list of doubles is 37, 97, 487, 4621.
%C A396456 For large numbers the average gap from a prime-complete number to the following prime grows on the same order as prime gaps, approximately log(n). The largest gap from a prime-complete number to the following prime less than 10^12 is 289 at n = 508463628750 (2*3^4*5^4*7^3*11^4) followed by the prime number 508463629039.
%H A396456 Ken Clements, <a href="/A396456/b396456.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A396456 a(n) = A151800(A055932(n+1)).
%o A396456 (Python)
%o A396456 from sympy import prime, primefactors, nextprime
%o A396456 SEARCH_GOAL = 120 # Find this many terms
%o A396456 def is_prime_complete(n):
%o A396456     pf = primefactors(n)
%o A396456     return prime(len(pf)) == pf[-1]
%o A396456 last_prime_complete, results = 2, []
%o A396456 while len(results) < SEARCH_GOAL:
%o A396456     results.append(nextprime(last_prime_complete))
%o A396456     last_prime_complete += 2
%o A396456     while not is_prime_complete(last_prime_complete): last_prime_complete += 2
%o A396456 print(results)
%Y A396456 Cf. A055932, A151800, A377028, A394258.
%K A396456 nonn
%O A396456 1,1
